To fix the issue with newlines (\n) or carriage return (\r) characters in the response while using Node.js and the `https` module, you can use the `replace` function to replace those characters with an empty string ('').

Here's an example of how you can fix it:

```javascript
const https = require('https');

https.get('https://example.com/', (res) => {
  let data = '';

  res.on('data', (chunk) => {
    data += chunk;
  });

  res.on('end', () => {
    // Replace \n and \r characters with an empty string
    const cleanedData = data.replace(/[\n\r]/g, '');

    console.log(cleanedData);
  });
}).on('error', (err) => {
  console.error('Error:', err.message);
});
```

In the above example, the `replace` function is used to remove all occurrences of `\n` and `\r` from the received data before logging it. The regular expression `/[\n\r]/g` will match any newline or carriage return characters in the data string and replace them with an empty string.

By doing this, you can prevent any unwanted line breaks or carriage return characters from interfering with your application logic.

